	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Let <math>
                     <latex>R\from \RNr[3] \to \RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> be the rotation with the following properties:</para.body>
            </para>
			         <ul>
				           <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Axis of rotation: the line <math>
                           <latex>x=-z</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>y=0</latex>
                        </math> oriented by the vector <math>
                           <latex>(1,0,-1)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
				           <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Angle of rotation: 90° according to the RHR</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
			         </ul>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the matrix which represents <math>
                        <latex>R</latex>
                     </math> with respect to standard coordinates.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>R</latex>
                           </math> is represented by the matrix</para.body>
                     </para>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{S}}\ =\ 
\dfrac{1}{2}\, \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; \sqrt{2} &amp; -1 \\
-\sqrt{2} &amp; 0 &amp; -\sqrt{2} \\
-1 &amp; \sqrt{2} &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We begin by setting up an ONB adapted to the given situation: The unit vector representing the given orientation of the axis of rotation is <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n} = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1 , 0 , -1)</latex>
                        </math>. A unit vector perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{n}</latex>
                        </math> is <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a} = (0,1,0)</latex>
                        </math>. This yields</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\Vect{b} = \CrssPr{ \Vect{n} }{ \Vect{a} } = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1, 0 , 1)</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Consequently, with <math>
                           <latex>\alpha := \pi/2</latex>
                        </math>, the given rotation is represented by the matrix</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{B}}\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
\cos \alpha &amp; -\sin \alpha &amp; 0 \\
\sin \alpha &amp; \cos \alpha &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix converting from <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{a},\Vect{b},\Vect{n})</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates to <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{S}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}\ =\ 
\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\, \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\
\sqrt{2} &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>To convert from <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{S}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates to <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>-coordinates we use</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=	</latex>
                           </math>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <caption>Why is this so?</caption>
							                          <para>
                                    <para.body>By design, the columns of <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                                       </math> form an ONB of <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                                       </math>. So this is an orthogonal matrix and, therefore, its inverse is given by its transpose.</para.body>
                                 </para>
						                        </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <caption>Why is this so?</caption>
							                          <para>
                                    <para.body>By design, the columns of <math>
                                          <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                                       </math> form an ONB of <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                                       </math>. So this is an orthogonal matrix and, therefore, its inverse is given by its transpose.</para.body>
                                 </para>
						                        </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}^{-1} = \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}^{T}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore the matrix representing <math>
                           <latex>R</latex>
                        </math> in standard coordinates is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\aligned
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{S}}\ &amp;=\ C_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{B}}\, A_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{B}}\, C_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}} \\
	&amp;=\ 
\dfrac{1}{2}\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; \sqrt{2} &amp; -1 \\
-\sqrt{2} &amp; 0 &amp; -\sqrt{2} \\
-1 &amp; \sqrt{2} &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right] 
\endaligned

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Is <math>
                        <latex>R</latex>
                     </math> invertible? If so, describe its properties as a linear transformation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>Yes! <math>
                              <latex>R</latex>
                           </math> is invertible. It is the rotation about the axis oriented by <math>
                              <latex>(1,0,-1)</latex>
                           </math> through the angle 90° according to the LHR.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The transformation effect of any rotation can be reversed by rotating through the same angle in the opposite direction. In particular, <math>
                           <latex>R</latex>
                        </math> is invertible, and <math>
                           <latex>R^{-1}</latex>
                        </math> is the rotation about the axis oriented by <math>
                           <latex>(1,0,-1)</latex>
                        </math> through the angle 90° according to the LHR.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
